829,-0.02265760,0.06946318,0.01427300,0.03474535,-0.04243644,0.09299292,0.03417898,0.07252258,0.00908695,0.13088106,-0.01968616,0.00652379,0.00067628,0.05826383,-0.03499224,0.05540368,0.00773095,-0.05486484,0.00301378,-0.09789680,-0.01671041,0.03164583,-0.04830004,0.01031218,-0.01134900,-0.00937395,-0.02425699,0.00641430,0.00066579,0.02514712,0.01503409,0.03706242,0.01028758,0.01424437,0.00837213,-0.06481890,0.05094553,0.08120701,0.03187237,0.02843410,0.06073631,-0.01610873]',E'Type Annotations and Tooling { #type-annotations-and-tooling }\n\nFirst let''s see how editors, mypy and other tools would see this.\n\n`BaseUser` has the base fields. Then `UserIn` inherits from `BaseUser` and adds the `password` field, so, it will include all the fields from both models.\n\nWe annotate the function return type as `BaseUser`, but we are actually returning a `UserIn` instance.\n\nThe editor, mypy, and other tools won''t complain about this because, in typing terms, `UserIn` is a subclass of `BaseUser`, which means it''s a *valid* type when what is expected is anything that is a `BaseUser`.','{"source": "fastapi", "version": "0.136", "language": "python", "title": "Response Model - Return Type { #response-model-return-type }", "section_title": "response-model", "url": "https://github.com/fastapi/fastapi/blob/master/docs/en/docs/tutorial/response-model.md", "topics": "fastapi,async,response,model", "categories": "web,python,rest,async"}');
